{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659686"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20884"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20884"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96697"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13759"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20884"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79326"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11793"},{"type":"tags","id":"11794"},{"type":"tags","id":"12709"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33153"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96697"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFamilial hypercholesterolemia is an autosomal dominant disorder characterised by elevated serum cholesterol levels, premature atherosclerosis, and tendinous xanthomas. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary pathophysiological mechanism in familial hypercholesterolemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased hepatic synthesis of cholesterol","Defective LDL receptor-mediated clearance of LDL","Reduced conversion of cholesterol to bile acids","Excessive intestinal absorption of dietary cholesterol","Impaired formation of high-density lipoprotein"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary pathophysiological mechanism in familial hypercholesterolemia is \u003Cstrong\u003Edefective LDL receptor-mediated clearance of LDL\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is most commonly (80-85% of cases) caused by mutations in the LDL receptor gene (LDLR), resulting in reduced numbers or function of LDL receptors. Less commonly, it is caused by mutations in the gene for apolipoprotein B-100 (5-10% of cases), which is the ligand for the LDL receptor, or by activating mutations in PCSK9 (1-2% of cases), which increases degradation of LDL receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll three mutation types result in impaired hepatic clearance of LDL from the circulation, leading to elevated serum cholesterol levels, which in turn causes premature atherosclerosis and tendinous xanthomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased hepatic synthesis of cholesterol\u003C/strong\u003E - While cholesterol synthesis may be secondarily affected, the primary defect is in LDL clearance, not synthesis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced conversion of cholesterol to bile acids\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not the primary mechanism in familial hypercholesterolemia, though it is involved in other disorders of cholesterol metabolism.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive intestinal absorption of dietary cholesterol\u003C/strong\u003E - Familial hypercholesterolemia is not primarily a disorder of intestinal cholesterol absorption.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired formation of high-density lipoprotein\u003C/strong\u003E - Familial hypercholesterolemia affects LDL metabolism, not primarily HDL formation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn heterozygotes with LDL receptor mutations, there is approximately 50% of the normal number of functional LDL receptors, resulting in a two- to three-fold elevation in plasma cholesterol. Homozygotes have virtually no functional LDL receptors and may have five- to six-fold elevations in plasma cholesterol, with much more severe clinical manifestations including myocardial infarction before age 20 years.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Familial hypercholesterolemia is most commonly caused by mutations in the LDL receptor gene, resulting in inadequate removal of plasma LDL by the liver.","Less common causes of familial hypercholesterolemia include mutations in apolipoprotein B-100 and proprotein convertase subtilisin/kexin type 9 (PCSK9).","All three types of mutations in familial hypercholesterolemia impair hepatic clearance of LDL, leading to increased serum cholesterol levels and premature atherosclerosis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 151-154"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79326"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20884"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79326"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T16:59:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T17:00:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13759"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96697"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"d